    <prp:abstract>High resolution NIR images of the grand-design spiral galaxy NGC 2997 obtained at VLT show a long
string of young stellar clusters with ages less than 7 Myr along its southern arm.  Individual ages
indicate an azimuthal age gradient consistent with the formation of the clusters being triggered
by a shock associated to a density wave. The aim of this proposal is to actually observe the gas
shock by detecting GMCs both in the up- and down-stream direction relative to the star-forming
front.  The typical size of GMCs is in the range of 50-200 pc corresponding to 0.5-2" at the
distance of NGC 2997.  We suggest to measure both velocities and densities of the GMCs using lines
of CO and CH3OH.  It is expected that a shock will introduce a radial velocity jump of 5-10 km/s.
A detection of such a jump would clearly proof the existence of a shock and allow to locate it.</prp:abstract>
